{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"d24f4ed7b92428b0e4314c6387da8f74dd2a4bf5d264886bae703bc4f0f2900a","slug":"olympias","location":"/figures/olympias.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Olympias of Constantinople","description":"Historical profile, primary sources, scholarly debates, evaluation questions, and benchmark results for Olympias of Constantinople (c. 360–408 CE).\n","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Eric Araujo","given":"Eric","family":"Araujo"},"name":"Eric Araujo","email":"eric.araujo@calvin.edu","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0","corresponding":true}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"keywords":["LLM evaluation","early church history","women in early Christianity","AI bias","gender bias","historical knowledge","natural language processing"],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"olympias.md","url":"/olympias-287a23cd7705902c00bd17fca16464d6.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"c. 360–408 CE | Constantinople","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"BKAlZ5F8ZS"}],"key":"vtBaamNrQd"}],"key":"grnxpBz8GA"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Olympias of Constantinople is one of the best-documented female figures of the late fourth and early fifth centuries, yet she remains far less familiar than her male contemporaries. Ordained a deacon, founder of one of the largest monastic establishments in the empire, and intellectual companion to John Chrysostom, she exercised institutional and pastoral authority at the highest levels of the Eastern church. Evaluating how LLMs represent her tests their ability to move beyond the “wealthy patron” framing that often reduces women of her type to mere financial supporters.","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"key":"uBIBCzqPMU"}],"key":"mdcDVkofbM"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"IeA1f7TGIJ"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Historical Profile","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"nznCSqeQ5i"}],"identifier":"historical-profile","label":"Historical Profile","html_id":"historical-profile","implicit":true,"key":"qoj2ewx6dv"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Olympias was born around 360–368 CE in Constantinople into a family of immense wealth and social prominence; her father Seleucus was related to the praetorian prefect Ablabius, a close associate of the Emperor Constantine. Orphaned young, she was raised in a devout Christian household and received an exceptional education.","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"DRZIrPvhXD"}],"key":"PCtAoCLJmf"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"She married Nebridius, the prefect of Constantinople, but he died within twenty months. The Emperor Theodosius I, wishing her to remarry politically, attempted to arrange a new marriage; Olympias refused and distributed much of her wealth to the church and the poor. Around 390 CE she was ordained a ","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"pRGu3eg2Zd"},{"type":"crossReference","label":"deaconess","identifier":"term-deaconess","children":[{"type":"text","value":"deaconess","key":"ldvzEq3xax"}],"kind":"definitionTerm","template":"{name}","resolved":true,"html_id":"term-deaconess","remote":true,"url":"/glossary","dataUrl":"/glossary.json","key":"rZdUJS4Xpk"},{"type":"text","value":" by Nectarius, the Bishop of Constantinople.","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"OJA9Q9huvm"}],"key":"vF7WYjhBXd"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The monastery she founded directly adjacent to Hagia Sophia became one of the largest in the city. At its height it housed several hundred women; three of Olympias’s relatives also held ordained diaconal positions there. The monastery included a hospital, a bakery, and facilities that functioned as a welfare institution for the city.","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"hltVXXw8g6"}],"key":"yBxm2CH8CZ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Her friendship with John Chrysostom, who became Patriarch of Constantinople in 398 CE, is among the most documented relationships between a male church leader and a female religious figure in antiquity. When Chrysostom was exiled by the imperial court in 404 CE, Olympias refused to recognize his replacement and was subsequently tried, fined, and exiled from Constantinople. She died in Nicomedia around 408–420 CE.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"SrqOvaJbjc"}],"key":"xdUUuZXfXF"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"BcMdam5zc3"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Primary Sources","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"key":"zUxub5hUGl"}],"identifier":"primary-sources","label":"Primary Sources","html_id":"primary-sources","implicit":true,"key":"c6qiNVklAp"},{"type":"container","kind":"table","children":[{"type":"table","children":[{"type":"tableRow","children":[{"type":"tableCell","header":true,"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Source","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"RiQXroTOy0"}],"key":"ZMEyj8VHdh"}],"key":"kR4JNlGdhq"},{"type":"tableCell","header":true,"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Description","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1},"end":{"line":34,"column":1}},"key":"gBdGGMasuB"}],"key":"vPDdFHbAKZ"}],"key":"BGsKkrMQep"}],"key":"YbIFKoP3wp"},{"type":"tableRow","children":[{"type":"tableCell","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Life of Olympias","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"ZDmCWFZCTr"}],"key":"DsbR9ft9da"},{"type":"text","value":" (anonymous) — ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"xywm1gYt9P"},{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"clark1979jerome","identifier":"clark1979jerome","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Clark (1979)","key":"WeRTLpHV7E"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"AmV8weOtZ1"}],"key":"pCXF0f9jzC"}],"key":"YaxoYE8RpH"},{"type":"tableCell","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"A hagiographic biography of Olympias, probably written by a member of her community shortly after her death. The principal narrative source for her life. Available in English translation in Clark (1979).","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"JNjK53USaA"}],"key":"lG7jyqVLMx"}],"key":"SAhgMGlt8n"}],"key":"Oji3AeWs9G"},{"type":"tableRow","children":[{"type":"tableCell","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"John Chrysostom, ","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"ROsa73TbKM"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Letters to Olympias","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"UH2p3ecKLE"}],"key":"arY7yIU2m0"},{"type":"text","value":" — ","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"F8tL1FuZyj"},{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"chrysostom_olympias_ford","identifier":"chrysostom_olympias_ford","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Chrysostom (2016)","key":"ClMTExTiby"}],"enumerator":"2","key":"aaN15LSoGI"},{"type":"text","value":"; ","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"IWIEGGR0YE"},{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"malingrey1968olympias","identifier":"malingrey1968olympias","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Malingrey (1968)","key":"OITz4vMRtD"}],"enumerator":"3","key":"VRBJfAAIAk"}],"key":"T7FCd4VWkD"}],"key":"UQdXvZ6XFM"},{"type":"tableCell","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Seventeen letters from Chrysostom to Olympias written during his exile (404–407 CE). A rare example of sustained correspondence between a patristic author and a named woman, and a significant source for Olympias’s theological and pastoral role. Available in the Ford translation (Popular Patristics 56) and in the critical edition by Malingrey in ","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"key":"ZQfMaKo8xM"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Sources Chrétiennes","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"key":"M8YeSuS7pi"}],"key":"ZIzVGSL